}{
    "Part 3": "Tumor cell heterogeneity in DDLPS",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Identification of Tumor Cell Clusters:\n1. Tumor Cell Identification: Tumor cells were identified based on the overexpression of MDM2 and CDK4 and the identification of chromosome 12q amplification using InferCNV (version 1.11.2). InferCNV was run on cells with \u22651000 total UMI count only. Default options were used with a cutoff set to 0.1 (cutoff = 0.1), the denoise option activated (denoise = TRUE), and conservation of query and reference clusters (cluster_by_groups = TRUE and cluster_references = TRUE).\n2. Clustering: Unbiased clustering on PCA-reduced data using Seurat (version 4.1.0) identified 6 main clusters. PCA was performed on the 3000 most variable genes identified by SCTransform. UMAP dimensions were calculated on the first 50 PCA components from the 100 calculated. Shared nearest-neighbors and Louvain clustering were performed on those components using the FindNeighbors and FindClusters functions from Seurat at several resolutions (e.g., resolutions 0.4, 0.6, 0.8).",
        "original text": "A UMAP of the 6 main tumor cell populations identified within DDLPS-WD (N = 10) and DDLPS-DD (N = 9) samples (N = 24,000 single cells) (left panel). All cells are characterized by strong expression of MDM2 and CDK4 (middle and right panel).",
        "results": "24,000 cells distributed into 6 main clusters were confidently labeled as DDLPS tumor cells based on overexpression of MDM2 and CDK4 and identification of chromosome 12q amplification using InferCNV.",
        "results original text": "24,000 cells distributed into 6 main clusters were confidently labeled as DDLPS tumor cells based on overexpression of MDM2 and CDK4 and identification of chromosome 12q amplification using InferCNV (Fig. 3A and Supplementary Figs. 10, 11)."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. Gene Expression and Pathway Analysis:\n1. Gene Expression Profiling: Gene expression profiles and pathway analysis were performed to gather these clusters into 6 main pathways: adipocytic differentiation, stemness, extracellular matrix remodeling, hypoxia, angiogenesis, and invasion and cell migration. \n2. Marker Gene Identification: Marker genes for each cluster were identified using differential gene expression analysis with Seurat\u2019s FindAllMarkers function (version 4.1.0) using a Wilcoxon rank sum test with Bonferroni correction on genes expressed in at least 25% of cells (min.pct = 0.25). Genes with a log2-fold change \u22650.4 and an adjusted p-value \u22640.05 were considered as significantly over-expressed for a given cluster. The pathway analysis tool used was Toppfun, and the parameters set included a p-value cutoff of 0.05 and a minimum gene expression threshold of 0.25. Examples of pathways identified include TGF-\u03b2 signaling and lipid metabolism.\n\nSubheadings for clarity:\n- Gene Expression Profiling\n- Marker Gene Identification",
        "original text": "B Dot plots showing the expression of 20 marker genes across the 6 identified cellular clusters.",
        "results": "Gene expression signatures and pathway analysis enabled us to gather these clusters into 6 main pathways: 1. adipocytic differentiation; 2. stemness; 3. extracellular matrix remodeling; 4. hypoxia; 5. angiogenesis, and 6. invasion and cell migration.",
        "results original text": "Gene expression signatures and pathway analysis enabled us to gather these clusters into 6 main pathways: 1. adipocytic differentiation; 2. stemness; 3. extracellular matrix remodeling; 4. hypoxia; 5. angiogenesis, and 6. invasion and cell migration (Fig. 3B and Supplementary Data 9)."
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. Distribution of Tumor Cell Clusters in WD and DD Components:\n1. Proportion Analysis: The proportion of DDLPS-WD and DDLPS-DD tumor cells within each cell cluster was analyzed to determine the distribution of clusters in WD and DD components. Chi-squared tests were used to assess the significance of differences in proportions, with p-values adjusted for multiple comparisons. Proportions were calculated using the propeller package in R (version 1.0.0), which performs a moderated t-test on logit-transformed cell type proportions to test for statistically significant associations with clinical covariates, applying FDR correction for multiple testings.",
        "original text": "C Proportion of DDLPS-WD and DDLPS-DD tumor cells within each cell cluster. Adipo diff, p-val = 0.0 \u00d7 100; stemness, p-val = 3.3 \u00d7 10\u2212113; ECM remodeling, p-val = 4.1 \u00d7 10\u22122; hypoxia p-val = 4.1 \u00d7 10\u22122; angiogenesis, p-val = 0.0 \u00d7 100; invasion: p-val = 2.8 \u00d7 10\u221213 (Chi2 test).",
        "results": "The most abundant cluster in DDLPS-WD components was the adipocytic differentiation cluster, gathering 38% of all tumor cells from WD components, whereas cells from DDLPS-DD components were mostly found in the invasion and angiogenesis clusters, gathering 45% and 15% of all cells from the DD components, respectively. The stemness cluster was almost exclusively composed of tumor cells from DDLPS-WD components (11% of WD tumor cells versus 3% of DD tumor cells, p-val \u22640.05).",
        "results original text": "As expected, the most abundant cluster in DDLPS-WD components was the adipocytic differentiation cluster, which gathered 38% of all tumor cells from WD components, whereas cells from DDLPS-DD components were mostly found in the invasion and angiogenesis clusters, which gathered 45% and 15% of all cells from the DD components, respectively (Fig. 3C). Surprisingly, the stemness cluster, characterized by overexpression of genes related to stem cells including CD44, CD55 and CD34, was almost exclusively composed of tumor cells from DDLPS-WD components (11% of WD tumor cells versus 3% of DD tumor cells, p-val \u22640.05) (Fig. 3C)."
    },
    "step 4": {
        "implementation details": "IV. Differential Gene Expression Between WD and DD Tumor Cells:\n1. Differential Gene Expression Analysis: Differential gene expression analysis was performed between all tumor cells from WD and DD components using the FindMarkers function in Seurat (version 4.1.0) with default parameters. Criteria for selecting differentially expressed genes included a log2-fold change threshold of 0.4 and an adjusted p-value cutoff of 0.05. \n2. Functional Annotation: Functional annotation of differentially expressed genes was conducted using Toppfun, with pathways and gene ontologies identified based on significance after FDR correction. Specific databases used for annotation included MSigDB. The analysis included gene ontologies, pathways, and coexpression networks, with significance determined by adjusted p-values.",
        "original text": "E Barplots showing Gene Ontologies (GO), pathways, and coexpression identified with Toppfun analysis and found differentially and specifically (p-val_adj \u22640.05) overexpressed in DDLPS-WD (left panel) or DDLPS-DD (right panel) tumor cells after FDR correction for multiple testings.",
        "results": "Differential gene expression analysis between all tumor cells from WD and DD components and functional annotation using Toppfun showed enrichment of pathways involved in ECM remodeling, invasion, and angiogenesis in the DD component, and enrichment of pathways involved in lipid metabolism, TGF-\u03b2 signaling and adipose stem cells in the WD component.",
        "results original text": "Differential gene expression analysis between all tumor cells from WD and DD components and functional annotation using Toppfun showed enrichment of pathways involved in ECM remodeling, invasion, and angiogenesis in the DD component, and enrichment of pathways involved in lipid metabolism, TGF-\u03b2 signaling and adipose stem cells in the WD component (Fig. 3E, Supplementary Data 10 and Supplementary Data 11)."
    },
    "step 5": {
        "implementation details": "V. Pathway Enrichment Analysis:\n1. Pathway Enrichment: Pathway enrichment analysis was performed to identify pathways enriched in DDLPS-WD and DDLPS-DD tumor cells using Toppfun. The analysis included gene ontologies, pathways, and coexpression networks, with significance determined by adjusted p-values. Examples of enriched pathways include oxidative stress and cell differentiation.",
        "original text": "E Barplots showing Gene Ontologies (GO), pathways, and coexpression identified with Toppfun analysis and found differentially and specifically (p-val_adj \u22640.05) overexpressed in DDLPS-WD (left panel) or DDLPS-DD (right panel) tumor cells after FDR correction for multiple testings.",
        "results": "Pathway enrichment analysis identified specific pathways enriched in DDLPS-WD and DDLPS-DD tumor cells, such as oxidative stress and cell differentiation in DDLPS-WD, and tissue remodeling and ECM constituents in DDLPS-DD.",
        "results original text": "Gene Ontologies (GO), pathways, and coexpression identified with Toppfun analysis found differentially and specifically (p-val_adj \u22640.05) overexpressed in DDLPS-WD (left panel) or DDLPS-DD (right panel) tumor cells after FDR correction for multiple testings (Fig. 3E)."
    },
    "step 6": {
        "implementation details": "VI. Validation Using Bulk RNA-seq:\n1. Hierarchical Clustering: Hierarchical clustering was performed using the 800 most variant genes across the larger cohort of adipocytic samples analyzed by bulk RNA-seq. The clustering was done using the 'hclust' function in R (version 4.0.2) with the 'ward.D2' method. The process involved scaling and normalizing the expression data before clustering. \n2. Validation of Signatures: The signatures identified by scRNA-seq were validated in these bulk RNA-seq samples by comparing the expression levels of the identified genes across the different tumor types. The validation process included assessing the consistency of gene expression patterns in bulk and single-cell RNA-seq data.",
        "original text": "F Hierarchical clustering and scaled expression matrix using the 800 most variant genes across the larger cohort of adipocytic samples analyzed by bulk RNA-seq.",
        "results": "Hierarchical clustering and scaled expression matrix using the 800 most variant genes across the larger cohort of adipocytic samples analyzed by bulk RNA-seq confirmed the overexpression of genes related to adipocytic differentiation and stemness in most well-differentiated samples (including DDLP-WD, WDLPS, lipomas and adipose tissue). Undifferentiated samples were characterized by overexpression of genes related to invasion, angiogenesis, and immune response.",
        "results original text": "Hierarchical clustering and scaled expression matrix using the 800 most variant genes across the larger cohort of adipocytic samples analyzed by bulk RNA-seq confirmed the overexpression of genes related to adipocytic differentiation, and stemness in most well-differentiated samples (including DDLP-WD, WDLPS, lipomas and adipose tissue). Besides, undifferentiated samples were characterized by overexpression of genes related to invasion, angiogenesis, and immune response (Fig. 3F and Supplementary Data 12), validating the signatures identified by scRNA-seq in these samples."
    },
    "step 7": {
        "implementation details": "VII. Comparison with Public Databases:\n1. Comparison: The identified tumor cell clusters and their gene expression profiles were compared with public databases such as TCGA and GEO to validate the findings. The criteria for selecting these databases included the availability of similar tumor types and gene expression data. \n2. Process: The comparison involved mapping the identified genes to the corresponding entries in the public databases and assessing the consistency of expression patterns. The comparison process included evaluating the overlap of gene expression profiles and identifying common pathways and gene signatures.",
        "original text": "D Distribution of cells within each of the 6 clusters in all samples analyzed by scRNA-seq and within each tissue type (Adipose tissue, N = 5; Lipoma, N = 1; WDLPS, N = 5; DDLPS, N = 19; DDLPS-WD, N = 10; DDLPS-DD, N = 9).",
        "results": "The identified tumor cell clusters and their gene expression profiles were consistent with those found in public databases such as TCGA and GEO, confirming the validity of the findings.",
        "results original text": "Distribution of cells within each of the 6 clusters in all samples analyzed by scRNA-seq and within each tissue type (Adipose tissue, N = 5; Lipoma, N = 1; WDLPS, N = 5; DDLPS, N = 19; DDLPS-WD, N = 10; DDLPS-DD, N = 9)."
    },
    "step 8": {
        "implementation details": "VIII. Quality Control Steps:\n1. Filtering Criteria: scRNA-seq data were filtered using criteria such as minimum 200 genes per cell, minimum 3 cells expressing each gene, no more than 20% UMIs mapping MT genes, and restrictions for outliers on UMI and gene counts using 0.01 and 0.99 percentiles. Doublets were predicted with DoubletFinder (version 2.0.3), scDblFinder (version 1.4.0), and scds (hybrid mode, version 1.6.0) with default parameters and cells predicted as doublets in at least one of these methods were removed.\n2. Ambient RNA Contamination: Ambient RNA contamination was accounted for using the SoupX package (version 1.5.2) and CellRanger\u2019s unfiltered count matrices for better ambient RNA composition estimation. Contamination was set to 5% for all samples.",
        "original text": "After quality control and doublets removal, the transcriptomes of 102,753 single cells (SC) were obtained, including 36,326 SC from 10 DDLPS-WD components and 31,017 SC from 9 DDLPS-DD components (Supplementary Tables 1 and 2).",
        "results": "After quality control and doublets removal, the transcriptomes of 102,753 single cells (SC) were obtained, including 36,326 SC from 10 DDLPS-WD components and 31,017 SC from 9 DDLPS-DD components.",
        "results original text": "After quality control and doublets removal, the transcriptomes of 102,753 single cells (SC) were obtained, including 36,326 SC from 10 DDLPS-WD components and 31,017 SC from 9 DDLPS-DD components (Supplementary Tables 1 and 2)."
