    "step 6": {
        "implementation details": "Compare the Copy Number Variations (CNVs) of tumor ASPC to other tumor cells in matched WD and DD components from 4 DDLPS patients using inferCNV with parameters cutoff=0.1 and denoise=TRUE. Use endothelial cells as the reference cell type. Identify conserved CNVs in ASPC and additional private clonal and sub-clonal genomic alterations in both WD and DD components.",
        "original text": "To investigate whether these tumor ASPC found in the WD component of DDLPS could be the progenitors of DDLPS, we compared the Copy Number Variations (CNVs) of tumor ASPC to the ones of other tumor cells in matched WD and DD components from 4 DDLPS patients. Strikingly, tumor ASPC were characterized by very few CNVs except for chromosome 12q amplification. Moreover, CNVs present in ASPC were conserved in both WD and DD components of the same tumor, which showed additional private clonal and sub-clonal genomic alterations.",
        "results": "Tumor ASPC were characterized by very few CNVs except for chromosome 12q amplification. CNVs present in ASPC were conserved in both WD and DD components of the same tumor, which showed additional private clonal and sub-clonal genomic alterations.",
        "results original text": "Strikingly, tumor ASPC were characterized by very few CNVs except for chromosome 12q amplification. Moreover, CNVs present in ASPC were conserved in both WD and DD components of the same tumor, which showed additional private clonal and sub-clonal genomic alterations."
    },
    "step 7": {
        "implementation details": "Validate the early genomic divergence of WD and DD components from a population of tumor adipocyte stem cells related to ASPC. Confirm that WD and DD components acquire additional genomic events private to each component following clonal evolution.",
        "original text": "These results suggest that WD and DD components of DDLPS diverge early from a population of tumor adipocyte stem cells related to ASPC and later acquire additional genomic events private to each component, indicating also that the DD part does not come from the dedifferentiation of the WD part.",
        "results": "WD and DD components of DDLPS diverge early from a population of tumor adipocyte stem cells related to ASPC and later acquire additional genomic events private to each component.",
        "results original text": "These results suggest that WD and DD components of DDLPS diverge early from a population of tumor adipocyte stem cells related to ASPC and later acquire additional genomic events private to each component, indicating also that the DD part does not come from the dedifferentiation of the WD part."
    },
    "step 8": {
        "implementation details": "Establish four patient-derived xenograft (PDX) models from the DD component of four different DDLPS tumors. Use NOD/SCID mice for engraftment and maintain ethical considerations as per institutional guidelines. Validate the morphological, immunohistochemical, and genomic profiles of PDX models to confirm they recapitulate the phenotypic aspects of the human DD component of DDLPS. Perform single-cell suspension and culture PDX cells in the presence of adipocytic differentiation cocktail (ADC: 66 nM insulin, 3 \u00b5M rosiglitazone, 86 \u00b5M IBMX, 0.1 \u00b5g/ml transferrin, 1 nM T3, 100 nM hydrocortisone) or osteogenic differentiation cocktail (ODC: StemMACS OsteoDiff medium). Assess the differentiation properties of tumor cells and the effect of TGF-\u03b2 (10 ng/ml) and TGF-\u03b2 receptor inhibitors (SB431542 or galunisertib, 10 \u00b5M) on adipocytic differentiation using RT-qPCR analysis and specific staining (Bodipy for adipocytic differentiation, Alizarin red for osteogenic differentiation). Include flow cytometry as an additional validation technique to confirm the presence and properties of progenitor cells.",
        "original text": "To define whether DDLPS tumor cells kept the biological properties of their progenitors, we used four patient-derived xenograft (PDX) models established from the DD component of four different DDLPS tumors. The pathological review showed that all models recapitulated the phenotypic aspect of the human DD component of DDLPS, with a proliferation of high-grade, undifferentiated tumor cells expressing MDM2. Next Generation Sequencing of PDX tumor DNA confirmed genomic profiles in accordance with DDLPS, with 12q amplification containing MDM2 and CDK4 in all models. The morphological, immunohistochemical and genomic profiles of PDX remained stable over tumor passages. Single-cell suspensions of the PDX were obtained, and cells were subsequently cultivated ex vivo in the presence of adipocytic differentiation cocktail (ADC) or osteogenic differentiation cocktail (ODC) for 14 or 21 days, respectively, before RT-qPCR analysis and specific staining. In all four PDX models, tumor cells showed striking pluripotent properties and were able to differentiate into both lineages as shown by the induction of expression of genes indicative of differentiation, and positive staining with Bodipy or Alizarin red dyes, indicative of adipocytic and osteogenic differentiation, respectively.",
        "results": "In all four PDX models, tumor cells showed striking pluripotent properties and were able to differentiate into both adipocytic and osteogenic lineages. TGF-\u03b2 treatment inhibited adipocytic differentiation properties of tumor cells, whereas TGF-\u03b2 receptor inhibitors SB431542 and galunisertib restored adipocytic differentiation.",
        "results original text": "In all four PDX models, tumor cells showed striking pluripotent properties and were able to differentiate into both lineages as shown by the induction of expression of genes indicative of differentiation, and positive staining with Bodipy or Alizarin red dyes, indicative of adipocytic and osteogenic differentiation, respectively."
    }
