    "Part 5": "Genomic evolution of DDLPS",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Shallow Whole Genome Sequencing (shWGS)\nA. DNA Extraction:\n\u2460 Extract DNA from frozen tumor samples after 2 hours of incubation with 200 \u00b5l proteinase K (20 mg/ml) at 56\u00b0C and 1 hour with 200 \u00b5l RNAse A (10 mg/ml) at 37\u00b0C, followed by phenol/chloroform extraction. Use 1 ml Phase Lock Gel Light (Eppendorf) to separate phases. Use 500 \u00b5l phenol and 500 \u00b5l chloroform for extraction.\nB. DNA Quality Control:\n\u2461 Measure DNA concentration using a nanodrop spectrophotometer and a qubit dsDNA BR Assay Kit. Ensure A260/A280 \u22651.8 and A260/A230 \u22651.9 for optimal labeling yield.\nC. Library Preparation:\n\u2462 Prepare sequencing libraries from 50 ng of DNA using the Agilent SureSelect XT-HS Target Enrichment System for Illumina Paired-End Multiplex Sequencing kit. Purify the libraries using 1.8x AMPure XP beads and perform quality checks using a Bioanalyzer.\nD. Sequencing:\n\u2463 Perform 100 bp paired-end sequencing on an Illumina NovaSeq 6000 platform, aiming for a sequencing depth of 1500X and a minimum coverage of 300X. Use PhiX control to monitor sequencing quality and handle low-quality reads by trimming using Trimmomatic with the following parameters: LEADING:3 TRAILING:3 SLIDINGWINDOW:4:15 MINLEN:36.",
        "original text": "DNA was extracted from frozen tumor samples after 2 hours of incubation with proteinase K and 1 h with RNAse A, by a phenol/chloroform and Phase Lock Gel Light (Eppendorf, Hamburg, Germany) procedure. Quantity and quality were estimated in 2 steps. First, a nanodrop spectrophotometer was used to assess gDNA purity. For an optimal labeling yield, samples should have an A260/A280 \u22651.8 and A260/A230 \u22651.9. Then a qubit dsDNA BR Assay Kit was used to measure the double-stranded DNA concentration. 50 ng of DNA input was used to prepare the library with the Agilent SureSelect XT-HS Target Enrichment System for Illumina Paired-End Multiplex Sequencing kit in accordance with the manufacturer\u2019s protocol. The design uses 571 genes and an additional backbone of probes across the whole genome with an average resolution of one probe every 200 Kb. Additional use of the library allows the perform a complete CNV profile by shallow whole genome sequencing before the capture. This allowed us to determine a genomic profile spanning every chromosome. The copy number profile for each case was estimated using a combination of homemade R scripts and the facets package (v0.6.0) with a sex-specific unmatched-germline control, previously sequenced using the same panel for normalization. Libraries were sequenced over 2*100pb, including 10pb containing UMI (Unique Molecular Identifier) to reach an average depth of 1500X and a minimum depth of 300X on the region of interest.",
        "results": "The median number of CNVs detected across 296 segmented chromosomal regions distributed along the 22 chromosomes was 14 (range 7\u201373) in DDLPS-WD samples, and 26 (range 7\u201376) in DDLPS-DD samples. Analysis of CNVs in each paired WD and DD DDLPS components showed that the median number of shared CNVs between pairs was 11 (range 6\u201357), the median number of CNVs private to the WD component was 2 (range 0\u201316), and the median number of CNVs private to the DD component was 12 (range 1\u201340). Some pairs showed major differences in the CNVs profiles of both components, illustrating their early genomic divergence and independent clonal evolution.",
        "results original text": "The median number of CNVs detected across 296 segmented chromosomal regions distributed along the 22 chromosomes was 14 (range 7\u201373) in DDLPS-WD samples, and 26 (range 7\u201376) in DDLPS-DD samples (Supplementary Data 15). Analysis of CNVs in each paired WD and DD DDLPS components showed that the median number of shared CNVs between pairs was 11 (range 6\u201357), the median number of CNVs private to the WD component was 2 (range 0\u201316), and the median number of CNVs private to the DD component was 12 (range 1\u201340). Some pairs showed major differences in the CNVs profiles of both components, illustrating their early genomic divergence and independent clonal evolution (Fig. 5A)."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. Targeted Next Generation Sequencing (NGS)\nA. DNA Extraction:\n\u2460 Extract DNA from frozen tumor samples using the same method as for shWGS.\nB. Library Preparation:\n\u2461 Use the Agilent SureSelect CD Curie CGP panel to prepare libraries from 50 ng of DNA. Follow the manufacturer's protocol, including purification steps using 1.8x AMPure XP beads and quality checks using a Bioanalyzer.\nC. Sequencing:\n\u2462 Perform 100 bp paired-end sequencing on an Illumina NovaSeq 6000 platform, aiming for a sequencing depth of 1500X and a minimum coverage of 300X. Use PhiX control to monitor sequencing quality and handle low-quality reads by trimming using Trimmomatic.\nD. Quality Control:\n\u2463 Use FastQC and MultiQC for initial quality control, and coverage quality control per sample using a combination of awk, Samtools mpileup, and bedtools intersect.",
        "original text": "The design of a custom next-generation sequencing (NGS) panel called DRAGON (for the Detection of Relevant Alterations in Genes involved in Oncogenetics by NGS) and marketed by Agilent under the name of SureSelect CD Curie CGP has been developed specifically for the genomic analysis of tumors. It is composed of 571 genes of interest in oncology from diagnostic, prognostic, and molecular therapy points of view. The nucleotide sequence (variant calling is performed using Varscan2) as well as the number of copies (deletion and focal amplification) were explored. 50 ng of DNA input was used to prepare the library with the Agilent SureSelect XT-HS Target Enrichment System for Illumina Paired-End Multiplex Sequencing kit in accordance with the manufacturer\u2019s protocol. The design uses 571 genes and an additional backbone of probes across the whole genome with an average resolution of one probe every 200 Kb. Additional use of the library allows the perform a complete CNV profile by shallow whole genome sequencing before the capture. This allowed us to determine a genomic profile spanning every chromosome. The copy number profile for each case was estimated using a combination of homemade R scripts and the facets package (v0.6.0) with a sex-specific unmatched-germline control, previously sequenced using the same panel for normalization. Libraries were sequenced over 2*100pb, including 10pb containing UMI (Unique Molecular Identifier) to reach an average depth of 1500X and a minimum depth of 300X on the region of interest. Read alignment was performed with BWA mem (v0.7.15) on the Human reference genome (hg19 assembly). Quality controls were performed using FastQC (v0.11.5) and MultiQC (v1.7), and coverage quality control per sample was performed using a combination of awk, Samtools mpileup, and bedtools intersect.",
        "results": "The median number of SNVs detected in the 571 genes covered by the DNA panel in DDLPS-WD samples was 1 (range 0\u20134), and the median number of SNVs detected in DDLPS-DD samples was 1 (range 0\u20136). Analysis of SNVs between paired WD and DD samples showed that 100% of SNVs were private either to the WD or to the DD component of each tumor.",
        "results original text": "The median number of SNVs detected in the 571 genes covered by the DNA panel in DDLPS-WD samples was 1 (range 0\u20134), and the median number of SNVs detected in DDLPS-DD samples was 1 (range 0\u20136) (Supplementary Data 16). Analysis of SNVs between paired WD and DD samples showed that 100% of SNVs were private either to the WD or to the DD component of each tumor (Fig. 5D)."
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. Sequencing Library Preparation\nA. DNA Extraction:\n\u2460 Extract DNA from frozen tumor samples using the same method as for shWGS.\nB. Library Preparation:\n\u2461 Use the Agilent SureSelect CD Curie CGP panel to prepare libraries from 50 ng of DNA. Follow the manufacturer's protocol, including purification steps using 1.8x AMPure XP beads and quality checks using a Bioanalyzer.\nC. Sequencing:\n\u2462 Perform 100 bp paired-end sequencing on an Illumina NovaSeq 6000 platform, aiming for a sequencing depth of 1500X and a minimum coverage of 300X. Use PhiX control to monitor sequencing quality and handle low-quality reads by trimming using Trimmomatic.",
        "original text": "The design of a custom next-generation sequencing (NGS) panel called DRAGON (for the Detection of Relevant Alterations in Genes involved in Oncogenetics by NGS) and marketed by Agilent under the name of SureSelect CD Curie CGP has been developed specifically for the genomic analysis of tumors. It is composed of 571 genes of interest in oncology from diagnostic, prognostic, and molecular therapy points of view. The nucleotide sequence (variant calling is performed using Varscan2) as well as the number of copies (deletion and focal amplification) were explored. 50 ng of DNA input was used to prepare the library with the Agilent SureSelect XT-HS Target Enrichment System for Illumina Paired-End Multiplex Sequencing kit in accordance with the manufacturer\u2019s protocol. The design uses 571 genes and an additional backbone of probes across the whole genome with an average resolution of one probe every 200 Kb. Additional use of the library allows the perform a complete CNV profile by shallow whole genome sequencing before the capture. This allowed us to determine a genomic profile spanning every chromosome. The copy number profile for each case was estimated using a combination of homemade R scripts and the facets package (v0.6.0) with a sex-specific unmatched-germline control, previously sequenced using the same panel for normalization. Libraries were sequenced over 2*100pb, including 10pb containing UMI (Unique Molecular Identifier) to reach an average depth of 1500X and a minimum depth of 300X on the region of interest."
    },
    "step 4": {
        "implementation details": "IV. Data Processing and Quality Control\nA. Read Alignment:\n\u2460 Align reads to the human reference genome (hg19) using BWA mem (v0.7.15).\nB. Quality Control:\n\u2461 Perform quality control using FastQC (v0.11.5) and MultiQC (v1.7).\nC. Coverage Quality Control:\n\u2462 Use a combination of awk, Samtools mpileup, and bedtools intersect for coverage quality control per sample, setting thresholds for read quality (Q30) and coverage (\u226530X). Address any issues by re-sequencing or using alternative alignment strategies.",
        "original text": "Read alignment was performed with BWA mem (v0.7.15) on the Human reference genome (hg19 assembly). Quality controls were performed using FastQC (v0.11.5) and MultiQC (v1.7), and coverage quality control per sample was performed using a combination of awk, Samtools mpileup, and bedtools intersect.",
        "results": "Read alignment and quality control were performed successfully, ensuring high-quality sequencing data for further analysis.",
        "results original text": "Read alignment was performed with BWA mem (v0.7.15) on the Human reference genome (hg19 assembly). Quality controls were performed using FastQC (v0.11.5) and MultiQC (v1.7), and coverage quality control per sample was performed using a combination of awk, Samtools mpileup, and bedtools intersect."
    },
    "step 5": {
        "implementation details": "V. Analysis of Copy Number Variations (CNVs)\nA. CNV Calling:\n\u2460 Use homemade R scripts and the facets package (v0.6.0) with a sex-specific unmatched-germline control for CNV calling. Set a minimum mapping quality of 0 and a minimum base quality of 15.\nB. CNV Annotation:\n\u2461 Annotate CNVs with the targeted genes of the panel and combine segments into 296 chromosomal regions for analysis. Extract focal (<10 Mb) amplifications and homozygous deletions from the hyper-segmented profile and aggregate with the normal profile.",
        "original text": "Copy number alterations were called using the combination of homemade R scripts (v3.2.0, R Core Team, 2015) and facets package v0.6.0 with a minimum mapping quality of 0 and a minimum base quality of 15. Focal ( < 10 Mb) amplification and homozygous deletion were extracted from the hyper-segmented profile and aggregated with the normal profile. The resulting segments were then annotated with the targeted genes of the panel. The number of breakpoints was computed per sample in the case of normal segmentation. The genomic profiles obtained after shWGS contained 52,725 segments that were combined into 296 final chromosomal regions containing the largest and most discriminant alterations spanning the 22 chromosomes.",
        "results": "The only recurrent shared alteration in all pairs was the 12q amplification containing MDM2 and CDK4.",
        "results original text": "The only recurrent shared alteration in all pairs was the 12q amplification containing MDM2 and CDK4 (Fig. 5B, C)."
